---------------------------------------------------------------  Market action since Sydney’s end of day:  EQUITIES
New York: U.S. stocks rose, erasing earlier losses and sending
benchmark indexes to five-month highs, as Federal Reserve policy
makers indicated they are ready to pump more cash into the
economy to protect the recovery.
* U.S. Steel Corp. fell 2 percent after South Korean rival Posco,
the world’s third-largest steelmaker, reported its first decline
in earnings in four quarters.
*The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 18.16 points, or 0.2
percent, to 11,028.5 after earlier tumbling as much as 97 points.
*The S&P 500 climbed 0.4 percent to 1,169.91 at 3:22 p.m. in
New York after sliding 0.8 percent earlier.  London: European stocks  retreated as a slump in a U.K. house-
price gauge fueled concern that the equities rally has outpaced
prospects for the economy.
*Punch Taverns Plc, the largest U.K. pub owner, tumbled 11
percent after reporting a 218 million-pound ($346 million)
impairment charge.
*The benchmark Stoxx Europe 600 Index lost 0.3 percent to
262.48 at the 4:30 p.m. close in London.  Tokyo: Japanese stocks  fell, with the Nikkei 225 Stock Average
dropping the most in a month. Carmakers slid on speculation the
yen will remain strong against the dollar as the U.S. Federal
Reserve eases monetary policy.
*Toyota Motor Corp. lost 1.5 percent. Honda Motor Co., Japan’s
second-largest carmaker, sank 2 percent.
*The Nikkei 225  lost 2.1 percent to 9,388.64 at the 3 p.m.
close in Tokyo, the biggest decline since Sept. 8.
*The Topix index fell 1.8 percent to 824.60, with about 20
stocks retreating for each that rose.  Sydney/Wellington: Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index fell 1.7
percent to 4,618.20, the biggest drop since Aug. 11, at the
4:10 p.m. close of trading in Sydney. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index
slipped 0.1 percent to 3,230.83 at the 5 p.m. close in
Wellington.  FOREIGN EXCHANGE  New York: The dollar dropped toward a 15-year low against the
yen and a record versus the Swiss franc as minutes of the
Federal Reserve’s September meeting showed the central bank was
poised to ease monetary policy “before long.” The euro
appreciated against the dollar on speculation the European
Central Bank will end purchases of bonds before the Fed.
*The dollar fell 0.3 percent to 81.85 yen at 3:23 p.m. in
New York.
*The euro gained 0.4 percent to $1.3927, from $1.3876, after
sliding 0.7 percent.  TREASURIES  New York: Treasury 30-year bonds fell for a third day on
speculation the Federal Reserve will buy shorter-maturity debt
and as the government prepared to sell $13 billion of the
securities this week.
*The yield on the 30-year bond rose four basis points, or
0.04 percentage point, to 3.79 percent at 2:50 p.m. in New York.
*Two-year note yields increased for the first time in nine days,
trading at 0.36 percent after earlier touching a record-low
0.327 percent.  COMMODITIES  GOLD  New York: Gold  declined for the first time in three days as a
rebound by dollar curbed demand for the metal as an alternative
asset.
*Gold futures  for December delivery fell $7.70, or 0.6 percent,
to settle at $1,346.70 at 1:48 p.m. on the Comex in New York.
*Silver  futures for December delivery fell 20.2 cents, or
0.9 percent, to $23.147 an ounce.  METALS  New York: Copper prices rebounded on forecasts that demand will
outpace shrinking supplies. Codelco Chief Executive Officer
Diego Hernandez said in an interview in London that he expects a
“tighter” market next year.
*Copper for delivery in three months rose $40, or 0.5 percent,
to $8,330 a metric ton ($3.78 a pound) at 5:10 p.m. on the
London Metal Exchange.  OIL  New York: Crude oil fell for a second day to below $82 a barrel
as the dollar strengthened, curbing the appeal of commodities as
an alternative investment.
*OPEC raised its forecast for 2010 global oil demand by 100,000
barrels a day to 85.59 million. That compares with 84.46 million
last year.
*Crude for November delivery  lost 52 cents, or 0.6 percent, to
$81.69 a barrel at 12:37 p.m. on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*Westpac’s monthly Australian Consumer Confidence Index at 10:30
a.m. in Sydney.
*New Zealand food price index at 10:45 a.m. in Wellington.
*Australian Bureau of Meteorology gives update on La Nina
weather event.
*Day 2 of AB+F Corporate and Business Banking Forum.  STOCKS TO WATCH: Stocks that may see unusual gains or
losses following news after the close yesterday:
*New Zealand’s government announced a variation in Teclom
Corp.’s undertakings  ANALYST RATINGS: Upgrades, downgrades, new coverage
